  "rationale": "In just two coach turns, the moves are precisely matched to what was just noticed and arrive at moments the client can receive them. Turn 2 catches the framing of the question itself rather than answering it — a classic AoA move (apply view to the voice / question the question) that invites self-inquiry without colluding with the victim frame. When the client deflects into 'detective work,' the coach mirrors her language ('I love that — detective work') to maintain rapport, then makes the deft move of pointing at 'to me' and offering 'What if you were also a suspect?' This is a frame-it-as-an-experiment / I-don't-buy-your-story move delivered as invitation, not accusation. It refuses the victim frame without fighting it. The sequence is appropriate — staying with framing/identity-level inquiry before any feeling work, which is right for a client this defended. No partner-picking advice, no collusion with disdain, no diagnosis. The pushback in turn 5 has not yet been met, so we can't see the next move, but the two moves shown are well-chosen and well-timed.",
